static INT WString::Compare (  const WString &  s1,
const WString &  s2,
BOOLEAN  ignore_case = TRUE,
BOOLEAN  locale_sensitive = TRUE
)  [inline, static]
 

Returns 0 if the WStrings s1 and s2 are equal, < 0 if s1 is less than s2, > 0 otherwise.

Parameters:
ignore_case If set to TRUE, the comparison is done case insensitive, hence the string L"ABC" is interpreted as equal to the string L"abc".
locale_sensitive If set to TRUE, a locale sensitive comparing is done. Locale sensitive comparing should be done for all sorted strings shown to the user.

const WCHAR* WString::GetCString (   )  const [inline]
 

Returns the WCHAR * pointer of the content of the object. Please be aware, that this returned pointer is never 0. Even if the wide character string is empty, this returned pointer will point to an empty, null terminated WCHAR * string. This means that using this method and comparing it's return value to 0 for testing the WString on emptyness is not correct - for checking on emptyness, the method IsEmpty() has to be used instead.

INT WString::LastIndexOf (  WCHAR  ch,
INT  from = -1
)  const
 

Returns the index within this wide character string of the last occurrence of the specified character ch, searching backwards starting at the specified index. If from is omitted the search starts at the end of the string. The position of the found character is returned (-1 is returned if the character has not been found).

WString::operator const WCHAR * (   )  const [inline]
 

Identical to GetCString(). Returns the WCHAR * pointer of the content of the object. Please be aware, that this pointer is never equal to NULL! Even if the wide ch string is empty, this returned pointer will point to an empty, null-terminated WCHAR * string! This means that using this operator and comparing it's value to NULL for testing the WString on emptiness is not correct - for checking on emptiness, the method IsEmpty() has to be used instead!
